					</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">R.B.S. and Lloyds Bank Say They&#8217;ll Move if Scotland Votes for Independence</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Chad Bray and Jenny Anderson			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-09-11T09:13:48+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">September 11, 2014 5:13 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">September 11, 2014 5:13 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/09/11/two-banks-say-theyll-move-if-scotland-votes-for-independence/" data-title="R.B.S. and Lloyds Bank Say They&#8217;ll Move if Scotland Votes for Independence" data-description="The moves by the Royal Bank of Scotland and the Lloyds Banking Group would be mostly technical. Both banks are expected to maintain jobs and significant banking operations in Scotland. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/12/business/12rbs-pic1/12rbs-pic1-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/12/business/12rbs-pic1/12rbs-pic1-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/12/business/12rbs-pic1/12rbs-pic1-blog480.jpg" id="100000003107577" width="480" height="321" alt="The Royal Bank of Scotland said it was looking at contingency plans if Scots vote for independence next week."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="321"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">The Royal Bank of Scotland said it was looking at contingency plans if Scots vote for independence next week.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Toby Melville/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="t11h46s" class="update">Updated, 11:46 a.m. | </span>LONDON &#8212; After months of trying to stay above the fray, two of Britainâs largest banks, Lloyds Banking Group and the Royal Bank of Scotland, said they would shift their bases to England if Scotland votes for independence next week.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The moves, if they happen, would be mostly technical in nature. Both banks are expected to maintain jobs and significant banking operations in Scotland.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But the potential changes are particularly significant in their symbolism: R.B.S. and Lloyds, through its Bank of Scotland unit, are among the financial institutions permitted to issue bank notes in Scotland. (Scotland uses the pound but issues its own notes that carry images of historic figures, like the poet Robert Burns, rather than an image of Queen Elizabeth II.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Clydesdale Bank, a unit of the National Australia Bank and the other institution allowed to issue pounds in Scotland, also announced plans on Thursday to shift its incorporation to England in the event of a âyesâ vote.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Polls in the last week indicated momentum shifting toward a vote for independence, prompting a push this week by Prime Minister David Cameron and other British politicians to persuade Scotland to keep the union intact. The independence vote is set for Sept. 18.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Many companies have stayed on the sidelines in the debate, perhaps hoping not to influence the outcome, but more are weighing in on the issue now.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Thursday, Martin Gilbert, chief executive of Aberdeen Asset Management, with Â£322.5 billion in assets under management, <a href="https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/news/politics/referendum/341701/martin-gilbert-scotland-will-prosperous-matter-vote/">said in an interview</a> with The Press and Journal newspaper that an independent Scotland âwould be a big success.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âMost sensible people now accept that Scotland would be prosperous with either outcome in the current constitutional debate,â he told the newspaper.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But a spokeswoman for Aberdeen said later Thursday that the asset manager would continue to be âneutralâ in the debate.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The financial service sector is enormous in Scotland, with the British government estimating that it was responsible for about 8 billion pounds annually, or about $12.9 billion. That represents about 8 percent of Scotlandâs gross domestic product.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The trade group Scottish Financial Enterprise estimated this year that the industry, directly and indirectly, employs about 12 percent of the Scottish work force, or about 200,000 people. Insurers, banks and asset managers are also major employers in Glasgow and Edinburgh, the countryâs two largest cities, according to the trade group.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The sectorâs dominance has ripple effects: More than 40 percent of postal services and 30 percent of accounting services are sold to the financial services sector. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Scotlandâs banking sector is particularly hefty. Britain&#8217;s banking system as a whole is about five times the size of its economy, and banking assets in Iceland before the financial crisis were nearly nine times larger than its economy. In Scotland, according to a report last year by the British government, banking assets were 12.5 times larger than the country&#8217;s gross domestic product, raising questions about Scotland&#8217;s ability to stabilize the banking system in the event of a future financial crisis. (Government support to the Royal Bank of Scotland since 2008 was <a href="https://www.blackrock.com/corporate/en-us/literature/whitepaper/investment-independence-scottish-referendum.pdf">equal to more than 210 percent</a> of Scotlandâs G.D.P., BlackRock wrote in a report in March.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">By shifting their homes to England, R.B.S., Lloyds and other banks would continue to enjoy the backing of the Bank of England as a lender of last resort and be eligible for deposit guarantees backed by the British government for their customers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAs part of such contingency planning, R.B.S. believes that it would be necessary to re-domicile the bankâs holding company and its primary rated operating entity (the Royal Bank of Scotland plc) to England,â the bank <a href="//www.rbs.com/news/2014/09/statement-in-response-to-press-speculation-on-re-domicile.html">said in a news release</a> on Thursday. âIn the event of a âyesâ vote, the decision to re-domicile should have no impact on everyday banking services used by our customers throughout the British Isles.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">R.B.S., founded in 1727, is one of Britainâs oldest banks. Its corporate headquarters are on a sprawling campus near the Edinburgh airport, and it employs about 11,500 people in Scotland.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bank said it intended to retain a significant level of its operations and employment in Scotland to support its customers there and the activities of the whole bank.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Lloyds confirmed late on Wednesday that it would move its domicile to England from Scotland if the referendum came out in favor of independence.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWhile the scale of potential change is currently unclear, we have contingency plans in place which include the establishment of new principal legal entities in England,â Lloyds said in a statement. âThis is a legal procedure and there would be no immediate changes or issues which could affect our business or our customers.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Thursday, the National Australia Bank, which operates Clydesdale and Yorkshire banks, and the personal finance arm of the supermarket operator Tesco also said they would shift the incorporation of their banking units to England in the event of a âyesâ vote.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The British government continues to own significant stakes in both Lloyds and R.B.S. after bailouts of both during the financial crisis.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Lloyds received a bailout of Â£17 billion, and the British government still owns about 25 percent of Lloyds after two stake sales in the last year to reduce its holdings.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The British government owns about 81 percent of R.B.S. after a Â£46 billion bailout.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Any changes in the banksâ status in Scotland are not likely to happen immediately. A vote in favor of independence would be followed by an 18-month transition period in which politicians in Scotland and England would negotiate a variety of issues ahead of a formal breakup, such as the allocation of military forces and treasury issues.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIn the event of a âyesâ result, the U.K. and Scotland could be plunged into a huge pool of uncertainty, as the negotiations that follow will undoubtedly be messy, and potentially damaging for the reputation of both countries,â Azad Zangana, an economist at Schroders, wrote in a research note on Thursday.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mark J. Carney, governor of the Bank of England, told a Parliament committee on Wednesday afternoon that the central bank would remain a lender of last resort for banks in Scotland during the transition period.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After that, it would be up to Scotland to determine who backed financial institutions, Mr. Carney said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Under European law, the country where a financial institution is incorporated, not the country in which those assets are situated, serves as the lender of last resort, Mr. Carney said. The rest of Britain, outside of Scotland, makes up a large portion of the deposit bases of both R.B.S. and Lloyds.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">George Osborne, the chancellor of the Exchequer, said this week that Britain would not share the pound with Scotland in a currency union if it voted for independence.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">No decision has been made on what currency Scotland might use if it goes independent.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Scottish pound notes issued by R.B.S., Lloyds and Clydesdale bank are backed by the Bank of England. Some merchants in northern England stopped taking Scottish bank notes this year in anticipation of the breakup.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It is possible that Scotland may opt to uses the pound for day-to-day transactions, a process known as sterlingization. Some countries in Latin America and in the Caribbean, for example, only use the United States dollar or use the dollar along with other currencies. By doing so, those countries opt for a more stable currency, but lack control over their own monetary policy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Carney, in his testimony on Wednesday, said countries that adopt another nationâs currency, without an official sharing agreement, often have to maintain larger levels of reserves to back that currency and gain the confidence of the public.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In an economy that is heavily tied to the financial services industry, as is the case in Scotland, the country often has to maintain reserves well above its gross domestic product, Mr. Carney said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The uncertainty about the effects of independence on the currency and on the banking sector extends to how much an independent Scotland could depend on North Sea oil reserves. Leaders in both the finance and energy sectors are warning against the perils of breaking away from Britain. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Wednesday, the energy company BP said it believed its prospects for oil exploration in the North Sea were âbest served by maintaining the existing capacity and integrity of the United Kingdom.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ben van Beurden, the chief executive of Shell, has previously said he would prefer that Scotland remain part of Britain. Both energy companies are large employers in Scotland.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Angus Grossart, chairman of Noble Grossart merchant bank and an influential figure in Scottish finance, said to The Financial Times that the impact of the referendum on the markets had been &#8220;severely overstated.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI think it is getting out of hand, a severe overreaction,â he said. âThe FTSE seems perfectly stable today, but to hear some of the comments you almost expect people to be predicting a plague of locusts or mice next.â</p>
<div id="addendums" class="addendums"><div class="story-addendum theme-correction"><strong>Correction: September 11, 2014</strong> <br>An earlier version of this article misstated the currency used by Hong Kong. Hong Kong uses its own dollar, which is pegged to the United States dollar at a fixed exchange rate. It does not use the United States dollar as its currency. 
</div></div>	</div>
